MPs belonging to the Economic Freedom Fighters have been removed from Parliament. CAPE TOWN - Members of Parliament (MPs) belonging to the Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) have been removed from Parliament.Screams could be heard as security forces removed EFF MPs. Some EFF MPs tried to resist the move, however they were overpowered as one by one they were led out of Parliament.Earlier, EFF leader Julius Malema and his caucus rose several times on point of orders, delaying the start of President Jacob Zuma s State of the Nation Address (Sona).#SONA2017 EFF MP&#39;S being kicked out of the NA chamber. KB pic.twitter.com/bF94mFQGut#SONA2017 EFF MPs comforting each other outside the Marks Building. They say they were hurt during their eviction from the house. LD pic.twitter.com/GZ45vJdyXyMP Godrich Gardee interrupted President Zuma as he was about to begin his address.From that point on, National Assembly Speaker Baleka Mbete and chairperson of the National Council of Provinces (NCOP) Thandi Modise had trouble returning calm to the National Assembly.[WATCH LIVE] Cope&#39;s Willie Madisha escorted out of the National Assembly... catch all #SONA2017 action live here: https://t.co/ImeJxwf0LF pic.twitter.com/ofdxATud0zCongress of the People (Cope)'s Willie Madisha was the first MP to be asked by NCOP chairperson Modise to leave the National Assembly.Madisha initially refused but was later escorted out of the House.#SONA Modise: Madisha has refused to leave, I&#39;m asking protection services to help him leave. SGBefore President Zuma could begin his address, Democratic Alliance MPs walked out of Parliament.Party leader Mmusi Maimane criticised the use of the military and slammed Zuma.&quot;The president has broken the law. This Parliament does not stand and we cannot stand for a violation of the Constitution.&quot;The Democratic Alliance then left.The Freedom Front Plus and Cope MPs followed suit by walking out of Parliament.Both the DA and the EFF addressed the media outsid